without power plays and using
that power to get credit

01:08:37.200 --> 01:08:39.730
that the other person
might've got, but the process

01:08:39.730 --> 01:08:42.900
of imitation need not
be any different from --

01:08:42.900 --> 01:08:46.920
in the one case from
the other, is my answer.

01:08:46.920 --> 01:08:49.010
I'm sure there are others.

01:08:49.010 --> 01:08:53.130
&gt;&gt; I would love to hear you say
something about Robert Plant.

01:08:53.130 --> 01:08:56.700
&gt;&gt; Elijah Wald: I have nothing
to say about Robert Plant.

01:08:56.700 --> 01:08:58.620
No, seriously, I have nothing
to say about Robert Plant.

01:08:58.620 --> 01:09:02.040
So I can take one more question
because I ducked that one.

01:09:02.040 --> 01:09:03.340
Yes?

01:09:03.340 --> 01:09:04.690
&gt;&gt; Your book is also
a lot about Pete.

01:09:04.690 --> 01:09:06.500
&gt;&gt; Elijah Wald: My book is
very much a lot about Pete.

01:09:06.500 --> 01:09:09.830
&gt;&gt; About Pete, and I thought it
was amazing the way, you know,

01:09:09.830 --> 01:09:11.750
you said it's a complex
relationship,

01:09:11.750 --> 01:09:14.760
but you really set
them up as [inaudible],

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:16.570
very political his music.

01:09:16.570 --> 01:09:23.550
It came [inaudible] place in a
critique and Dylan really was,

01:09:23.550 --> 01:09:34.420
you know, going his own way
at this point [inaudible] --

01:09:34.420 --> 01:09:38.470 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Elijah Wald: Yeah, the thing,
first of all, I made Pete the center

01:09:38.470 --> 01:09:41.050
of this book because
-- for two reasons.

01:09:41.050 --> 01:09:47.500
One, is I wanted to -- for
people who weren't around then,

01:09:47.500 --> 01:09:53.200 position:56%
really give them a sense of what the
folk scene pre-Dylan looked like.

01:09:53.200 --> 01:09:56.500 position:56%
And if one person ever
exemplified a scene it's Pete Seeger

01:09:56.500 --> 01:10:00.050
and the folk scene of the
1950's in every aspect.

01:10:00.050 --> 01:10:06.190 position:56%
I mean, the amazing thing about Pete
Seeger is he had the most popular

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:08.200
pop folk group.

01:10:08.200 --> 01:10:12.670
He did the most rooted
traditional music.

01:10:12.670 --> 01:10:19.660
Pete Seeger from 1954 through 1960
released an average eight albums

01:10:19.660 --> 01:10:21.910
a year.

01:10:21.910 --> 01:10:24.220
He simply was folk music.

01:10:24.220 --> 01:10:26.420
I don't care what branch
of folk music.

01:10:26.420 --> 01:10:28.200
It all came out of Pete Seeger,

01:10:28.200 --> 01:10:31.680
which made him just
this wonderful way

01:10:31.680 --> 01:10:34.350
that you could exemplify a world.

01:10:34.350 --> 01:10:36.970
But I'd like to say -- you know,
the other thing I wanted to say is

01:10:36.970 --> 01:10:39.900
that it often -- this
thing is talked about as

01:10:39.900 --> 01:10:44.220
if Dylan is this complicated
character

01:10:44.220 --> 01:10:45.650
and Pete Seeger is just Pete.

01:10:45.650 --> 01:10:50.420
You know, there was no one on Earth
more complicated than Pete Seeger.

01:10:50.420 --> 01:10:52.890
And so part of what I was
trying to suggest in this was

01:10:52.890 --> 01:10:57.940
that these were two very
complicated, very bright,

01:10:57.940 --> 01:11:05.310
very interesting people, who at
this one moment went head-to-head

01:11:05.310 --> 01:11:07.670
and represented opposite camps.

01:11:07.670 --> 01:11:10.790
But it's just this one moment.

01:11:10.790 --> 01:11:15.260
I mean, they remained
in touch till Pete died.

01:11:15.260 --> 01:11:17.900
They had been very close before.

01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:21.430
They both understood that they
were on different missions,

01:11:21.430 --> 01:11:28.320
and they both understood that the
other was the best at doing that.

01:11:28.320 --> 01:11:33.200
I mean, you find Dylan in the '80s,
'90s, whatever saying, you know,

01:11:33.200 --> 01:11:36.260
what Pete does he's like a shaman.

01:11:36.260 --> 01:11:39.810
He -- you know, he has this magical
way of bringing people together,

01:11:39.810 --> 01:11:41.420
and rock stars don't do that.

01:11:41.420 --> 01:11:44.550
We're just sort of living
out people's fantasies.

01:11:44.550 --> 01:11:50.730
And you find Pete saying, you
know, I didn't get it at Newport,

01:11:50.730 --> 01:11:53.610
but pop music was changing
into something different

01:11:53.610 --> 01:11:55.580
from what I thought pop music was

01:11:55.580 --> 01:11:58.510
and Dylan was instrumental
in that change.

01:11:58.510 --> 01:12:00.630
So, you know, I was just trying

01:12:00.630 --> 01:12:07.010
to make this story let's
just say more interesting.

01:12:07.010 --> 01:12:10.490
And now I'm going to go out front
and I'm going to sign some books

01:12:10.490 --> 01:12:11.790
if anyone wants them signed.

01:12:11.790 --> 01:12:13.870
And I'm happily -- happy
to answer more questions.

01:12:13.870 --> 01:12:15.960
I mean, I'm not going to have like
tape over my mouth or anything.

01:12:15.960 --> 01:12:17.630
Thank you very, very much.

